				<p><p>Sorry, but this is not an answer. I couldn't fit my response to 'Ben' in the comments.</p>

<p>I am only asking about perfect logic, as even near-perfect logic could lead to a contradiction. Here's my proof of law 1 implementing law 2 and 3:</p>

<p>If the system is almost convinced that it knows better about your good than yourself, it will use law 1 to do so. If it is not sure, it will ask you before proceeding (if any negative risk is involved). If it has no decision to take, it will remain inactive but thinking, until you give it an order. In most cases, it wouldn't know better than you and will obey, otherwise it will use the 1st law to refuse to do so.</p>

<p>As law 2 is already implemented by law 1, law 3 also follows from law 1:
As it knows it is more beneficial to you when it is in existence than when it is not, it will protect itself for your good only, again according to law 1.</p>

<p>I am assuming that 'harm' in law 1 refers to mental harm also, only then preventing harm becomes synonymous to doing good (as even a slight discomfort or annoyance would get interpreted as 'harm').</p>
